# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afl-video-game-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afl-video-game-series/1897-vfl-season] The **1897 VFL season** was the inaugural season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1897-vfl-season] The season ran from 8 May to 4 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a three-week finals series featuring the top four clubs.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1897-vfl-season] Eight Victorian Football Association (VFA) clubs – Carlton, Collingwood, Essendon, Fitzroy, Geelong, Melbourne, South Melbourne and St Kilda – featured in the inaugural season after seceding from the VFA in 1896.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1897-vfl-season] Essendon won the inaugural premiership after winning all three of its finals matches, with Geelong finishing as runners-up with two wins.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1897-vfl-season] Geelong won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1897-vfl-season] Geelong's Eddy James and Melbourne's Jack Leith tied for the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkickers.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1897-vfl-season] In 1897, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 20 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 20 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:afl-video-game-series/1897-vfl-season] Each team played each other twice in a home-and-away season of 14 rounds.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1897-vfl-season] Once the 14-round home-and-away season had finished, the 1897 VFL Premiers were determined according to the conditions dictated by the specific format and conventions of the 1897 Finals System, which was used in this season only.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1897-vfl-season] The following table can be sorted from biggest winning margin to biggest losing margin for each round.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1897-vfl-season] If two or more matches in a round are decided by the same margin, these margins are sorted by percentage (i.e. the lowest-scoring winning team is ranked highest and the lowest-scoring losing team is ranked lowest).
[src:afl-video-game-series/1897-vfl-season] Opponents are listed above the margins and home matches are in bold.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] The **1898 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Essendon Football Club and Fitzroy Football Club, held in Melbourne on 24 September 1898.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] The match was played to determine the premiers for the 1898 VFL season.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] The game was played under atrocious ground conditions in front of 16,538 people at the Junction Oval.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] The match is recognised as the first VFL grand final, although the term "grand final" was not in wide use until 1931.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] It was the first time that Victorian Football League premiership was decided in a final match, as the 1897 premiership was won under a different finals system by Essendon when they finished above three other clubs on the finals series ladder.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] Both Fitzroy back pocket Stan Reid and the Essendon full-forward Charlie Moore later died in South Africa in active service during the Anglo-Boer War—Moore on 5 May 1901, and Reid on 23 June 1901.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] During the 1898 home-and-away season, all teams played each other twice.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] The winners of the two sections were Fitzroy and Collingwood, respectively (for results of all of the round-robin matches); and, a week later (17 September 1898), the two teams played each other at Brunswick Street Oval, with Fitzroy winning the match 2.10 (22) to 1.5 (11).
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] After the VFL referred the decision to the VFL's Match Arrangement Committee, they, upon the express instructions of that committee, rejected the suggestions of the two teams outright and the match was controversially scheduled to be played at the Junction Oval.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] The Junction Oval was in an appalling condition, as the ground had not been used since the second Saturday of the sectional round-robin match three weeks earlier (3 September); and, since then, it had been thoroughly top-dressed and "cultivated" in anticipation of the coming cricket season.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] Also, the cricket ground's asphalt cycling track that lay between the boundary line and the fence presented a considerable danger to the footballers.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] Despite being the "challenger", Essendon flatly refused to play in the scheduled match, declaring that it would rather forfeit the match and the premiership than play on such a dangerous surface.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] This view was also strongly supported by Fitzroy, whose captain, Alec Sloan, had also taken the step of signing a statutory declaration to the effect that, in his opinion, the ground was entirely unfit to play on.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] The VFL, perhaps somewhat driven by the fact that the attraction of a finals system was one of the major reasons that the eight teams had left the VFA and formed the VFL in the first place, had a special meeting to hear Essendon's appeal.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] While it chose to endorse the committee's decision, it also did everything it could to convince Essendon to play the match.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon did not actually agree to play the match until the night before the game; ultimately, this "in-doubt-until-the-last-minute match" was still attended by 16,538 paying spectators; it certainly would have been a much larger crowd otherwise.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] The ground had been in such a dreadful condition that, in the week prior to the match, over 40 dray-loads of rubbish, soil and street-sweepings had been taken from the ground.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] All of this last-minute work greatly improved the playing surface at the ground, with sportswriters noting that while the ground was imperfect, it was nevertheless fit for use.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] Dry, windy weather and patches of ground where the topsoil had not bound meant that players often fell on the grassless slippery ground for want of some sort of grip, and play was often impeded by clouds of dust.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] To prevent any repeat of the events leading up to the 1898 challenge final, the VFL agreed that from 1899 they would schedule for a possible challenge final in advance.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] In 1898, all VFL teams had 20 on-the-field players and no "reserves".
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] Although there were no reserves, any player who had left the playing field for any reason at all could resume his place on the field at any time.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy selected a set of brothers in its team: Jim and Mick Grace (see TALK page).
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon had beaten Fitzroy in their round 1 and round 8 matches by 53 and 43 points, respectively.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy had beaten Essendon by 29 points in the third match of their round-robin Sectional matches.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] Both teams had great difficulty playing football in the appalling ground conditions—as evidenced by the low scores—and the tough, bustling Fitzroy team handled the conditions far better than the Essendon team that had hoped to spread the game out as far as possible.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy took the lead in the first few minutes of the match, and Essendon were never able to catch up.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon were further demoralized when Fitzroy champion forward and follower Mick Grace, renowned for his marking skill and kicking prowess, flew high over a pack to take a spectacular high mark and kicked a long-range goal.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] In a very tight, defensive second half, as the playing conditions deteriorated even further, only one goal was scored.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy went on to beat Essendon 5.8 (38) to 3.5 (23).
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-season] The **1898 VFL season** was the second season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 14 May to 24 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-season] Fitzroy won the premiership, defeating Essendon by 15 points in the 1898 VFL grand final; it was Fitzroy's first VFL premiership.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-season] Essendon won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-season] Collingwood's Archie Smith won the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkicker.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-season] In 1898, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 20 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 20 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1898 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-season] The VFL introduced a new system of finals for the 1898 season.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-season] The new system, which was used from 1898–1900, allowed all clubs to compete for the major premiership, with the minor premiers having the right to challenge for the premiership.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1898-vfl-season] By winning the minor premiership and accruing at least eight premiership points from its three sectional matches, Essendon won the right to challenge the semi-final winner for the premiership.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] It was the second annual grand final of the Victorian Football League.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 4,823 spectators, was won by Fitzroy by a margin of 1 point, becoming the first club to claim back-to-back VFL premierships.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy had won the minor premiership in the 1899 season, while South Melbourne had finished sixth after the home-and-away season.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] In the sectional major rounds, Fitzroy and South Melbourne each finished with records of 3–0 to qualify for the final.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] Under the finals system in place, this match was the final of the major round, played between the two section winners.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] Had South Melbourne won the match, it would not have immediately won the season's premiership; Fitzroy, as the minor premiers, would have had the right to challenge South to a rematch for the premiership on the following Saturday.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] Meanwhile, Fitzroy could clinch the premiership win a win in this match.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] "The last match of the season for the league premiership was played on Saturday, when Fitzroy and South Melbourne met on the St.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] Unfortunately, steady rain, which had fallen all the morning, continued nearly all the afternoon, making the conditions under which the game was played unsatisfactory for the players and most unpleasant for spectators.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] The "weather committee" had not met to consider the advisability of a postponement, and when the teams assembled South Melbourne suggested deferring the match until next Saturday, but Fitzroy preferred to brave the elements.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] The assembling of about 4000 spectators in the unfavorable circumstances indicated clearly that, if the weather had kept fine, the attendance would have been enormous.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] As it was, those present evinced keen interest in the game, every notable bit of good play being heartily cheered.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] Amongst the onlookers were a number of enthusiasts from Geelong, who came up by special train.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] had the ground in splendid order until the rain came, and even after the steady downpour, extending over many hours, it played very, much better than could have been expected, reflecting great credit on the experienced and skilful curator. ...
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] The strong wind from the southern end of the ground favoured South Melbourne in the opening quarter.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] Harry Lampe kicked the first two goals of the match, and Fitzroy's only score, a behind, came when a kick from Mick Grace hit the post.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy then had the advantage of the wind in the second quarter.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] Goals to Mick Grace and Fred Fontaine had them ahead at half time.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] Charlie Colgan gave South Melbourne the lead with the only goal of the third term.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] Bill McSpeerin's goal 15 minutes into the final quarter gave Fitzroy the win.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy's Bert Sharpe, the team's centre half-forward in its 1898 premiership side, was a late withdrawal from the side due to the death of his father the day before the Grand Final; his teammates wore black armbands for that match.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-season] The **1899 VFL season** was the third season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 13 May to 16 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-season] Fitzroy won the premiership, defeating South Melbourne by one point in the 1899 VFL grand final; it was Fitzroy's second (consecutive and overall) VFL premiership.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-season] Fitzroy also won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-season] Geelong's Eddy James won his second leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkicker.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-season] In 1899, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 18 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 18 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:afl-video-game-series/1899-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1899 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-grand-final] The **1900 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Melbourne Football Club and Fitzroy Football Club, held at the East Melbourne Cricket Ground in Melbourne on 22 September 1900.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-grand-final] It was the 3rd annual Grand Final of the Victorian Football League, staged to determine the premiers for the 1900 VFL season.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 20,181 spectators, was won by Melbourne by a margin of 4 points.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-grand-final] The winner of this match would win the premiership.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-grand-final] Arthur Sowden, and Bill Bowe were unable to play for the Melbourne team, due to injury, and Eric Gardner was unavailable.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-season] The **1900 VFL season** was the fourth season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 5 May to 22 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-season] Melbourne won the premiership, defeating Fitzroy by four points in the 1900 VFL grand final; it was Melbourne's first VFL premiership.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-season] Fitzroy won its second consecutive minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-season] Geelong's Teddy Lockwood and Essendon's Albert Thurgood tied for the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkickers.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-season] In 1900, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 18 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves", although any of the 18 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1900 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-season] The rescheduling of round 3 until after round 14, which occurred following the cancellation of the originally scheduled matches due to heavy rain, is also reflected in this table.
[src:afl-video-game-series/1900-vfl-season] By winning the minor premiership and accruing at least eight premiership points from its three sectional matches, Fitzroy won the right to challenge the semi-final winner for the premiership.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The ***AFL* video game series** is a series of Australian rules football video games licensed and based on the VFL/AFL.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] Released and licensed under the then-VFL branding of the AFL.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game involves playing a game of Australian rules football from a third-person perspective, with the ability to perform the basic actions of a typical player of the sport.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game can be played by one person, or by two players against each other.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] There is also a kick to kick mode, and a season mode where one to six players can play multiple games in a season finishing with a grand final.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was developed by Beam Software, and was published by Mattel.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was released solely for Microsoft Windows in 1996.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] Players could manage one of the 16 clubs of the 1996 AFL season.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was also the last video game in the series to feature the Fitzroy Lions and the Brisbane Bears as playable teams before they were merged.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game was also the first game to be developed by Blue Tongue Entertainment and was published by Cadability.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was released in 1997 for Microsoft Windows.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] 16 teams were available in the game and it was the first in the series to feature Brisbane Lions and Port Adelaide.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It is also the first game in the series to have commentary, which was provided by Bruce McAvaney.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game was developed by Creative Assembly and published by EA Sports.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was released in 1998 for the PlayStation and Microsoft Windows.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was based on the 1998 season and allowed play as any of the 16 teams.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The commentary is provided by Bruce McAvaney and Leigh Matthews.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game's music was composed by Jeff van Dyck.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was the first AFL video game to be developed by IR Gurus.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game was released as a PC only game.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The player assumes the role of an AFL Coach and issues commands such as the type of play the team should play (attacking, defensive, Normal) and when to interchange.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was released in 2002 for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 2 and Xbox.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game is based on the 2002 AFL season with team rosters.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was developed by IR Gurus and published by Acclaim Entertainment.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It is also the first game in the series to feature a live action intro of AFL games in the 2003 season.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] A release in North America was planned on PlayStation 2 and PC via the official AFL website for North America, USFooty.com.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was released for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 2 and Xbox in 2003.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game is based on the 2003 AFL season with team rosters based on that year.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] AFL Live 2004 includes all 16 official AFL teams and eight stadiums (MCG, Telstra Dome, Optus Oval, Kardinia Park, AAMI Stadium, Subiaco Oval, Gabba and SCG).
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It also included all 22 home and away matches and the finals series.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game was published by Acclaim with the song Lost Control by Grinspoon as the intro song.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was released for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 2 and Xbox on 29 April 2004.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game is based on the 2004 AFL season with team rosters based on that year.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was developed by IR Gurus and was the final AFL game to be published by Acclaim Entertainment, before their bankruptcy on 1 September 2004.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] This is the next edition after AFL Premiership Edition.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] When Acclaim shut down its operations in Australia, Sony Computer Entertainment got publishing and distributing rights to the game.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] Because Sony Computer Entertainment had an exclusive period with the title, initially it was only launched on PlayStation 2.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] However, THQ released a Microsoft Windows and Xbox version of the game.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was released on 22 September 2005 and is only available in Australia.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] AFL Premiership 2006 is the tenth game in the series.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] A follow-up to AFL Premiership 2005, it is based on the 2006 AFL season and was released only for the PlayStation 2.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The revamped kicking system requires the players to time the button presses to kick straight, because holding it down for too long results in the ball turning in the opposite side.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] There are several modes: training mode (provides the basics), short match, Wizard Cup, Premiership and Finals.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] A newly introduced multiseason allows the management of certain team aspects.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] That includes things like improving player skills, trading players at the end of the season, and putting the emphasis on draft.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It is a simulation game for the PlayStation 2 based on the AFL.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game marks the final AFL game to be developed by Australian games company IR Gurus and was published by Sony Computer Entertainment, IR Gurus seventh collaboration in the series, and was released on 28 June 2007.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game includes all 16 teams, more than 600 AFL players with updated stats and all of the major stadium.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] Game modes in AFL Premiership 2007 are Single Match, Season Mode, Career Mode, Mission Mode and Training Mode.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was a follow-up to AFL Premiership 2006.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was released for the PlayStation Portable.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game was developed by Wicked Witch Software and co-published by Tru Blu Entertainment and Sony Computer Entertainment.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game is based on the 2009 AFL season and includes all 16 teams and players.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was released for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 3 and Xbox 360 based on the 2011 AFL season.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was developed by Big Ant Studios and released on 21 April 2011.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The Game of the Year Edition, an updated version of the game for the 2012 AFL season was released on 6 June 2012.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was released for Wii the same year as *AFL Live*, based on the 2011 AFL season.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It features more management mechanics than *Live*, with a ten-year campaign, as well as multiplayer of up to 8 players.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] As with the other systems, a Game of the Year edition with 2012 players and locales was again released in June 2012.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was released for PlayStation 3 and Xbox 360 on 12 September 2013.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The 2014 Season Pack was released on 30 June 2014 for Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 on 9 July 2014.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] A mobile port was released on iOS on 28 May 2015 and Android on 26 September 2015.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was developed by Wicked Witch Software and was released on 5 May 2017, for PlayStation 4 and Xbox One, with the Microsoft Windows version released on 21 July 2017, via Steam.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The 2018 Season Pack was later released on 3 May 2018.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] Serving as a sequel to 2017's AFL Evolution, it was released in 2020.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The 2021 Season Pack was released on 7 May 2021.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game was developed by Big Ant Studios, whose last AFL title was *AFL Live* in 2011.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game's release on Xbox was delayed for unspecified reasons.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] The game includes all the features from the previous game and will include a new player career mode last seen in AFL Evolution 2.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] There is also a brand new marking technique.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] It was released in the Nintendo DS on 2 July 2009.
[src:afl-video-game-series/afl-video-game-series] Focused more on the League's mascots than on the sport itself, the central component of the game is the adventure the player's mascot experiences in the themed worlds.
